‡∞ö‡∞ï‡±ç‡∞∞‡∞Ç","updated_time":"2018-08-08T09:33:52+0000","id":"1295430967260725_2182254508720071"},{"message":"‡∞Æ‡∞® ‡∞ó‡±ç‡∞∞‡±Ç‡∞™‡±Å ‡∞ó‡±Å‡∞∞‡∞ø‡∞Ç‡∞ö‡∞ø ‡∞π‡∞®‡±ç‡∞∏‡±ç ‡∞á‡∞Ç‡∞°‡∞ø‡∞Ø‡∞æ ‡∞™‡±á‡∞™‡∞∞‡±ç‡∞≤‡±ã..\n‡∞∏‡∞≠‡±ç‡∞Ø‡±Å‡∞≤‡∞Ç‡∞¶‡∞∞‡∞ø‡∞ï‡∞ø ‡∞Ö‡∞≠‡∞ø‡∞®‡∞Ç‡∞¶‡∞®‡∞≤‡±Å ‡∞∑‡∞£‡∞æ‡∞∞‡±ç‡∞•‡±Å‡∞≤‡±Å..\nBringing back old Telangana padulu\n\nWords that resonate in villages have somehow not entered the modern lexicon, a Jagityal-based Sudheer Kumar Thandra who started ‚ÄòTelangana Padalu, Isirelu and Samskruthulu‚Äô on Facebook has brought the focus back on old words in Telangana by word of mouth and of course with help from social media\n\nThe group shares 15 words every day and the count doubles during weekends\nThey also plan to make district wise list of meaning of each word\nThe word ‚ÄòPaddy‚Äô has more than 70 meanings in Telangana region.\nWithin one year, the group managed to cover more than 8,000 words\n\nV Sateesh Reddy\n\nDo you know the meaning of the word ‚ÄòAmoodalollu‚Äô in Telugu? You don‚Äôt, right? It means ‚Äòtwins‚Äô in English language and in general Telugu, it was ‚ÄòKavala Pillalu‚Äô. Sounds interesting right! Yes, there are hundreds of words that were part of the daily lexicon in Telangana 50 years ago. With the passage of time, these words morphed and took on new forms. \nWith an objective to save all these words of Telangana, Jagityal-based Sudheer Kumar Thandra started a group titled, ‚ÄòTelangana Padalu, Isirelu and Samskruthi‚Äô literally translated as ‚ÄòWords, Tools, and Culture of Telangana‚Äô in Facebook. Until today, more than 6,700 members of Telangana joined in the group from all over the world.\nSpeaking with The Hans India, Sudheer Kumar Thandra, shared what drove him to start such a group. ‚ÄúWhen I visit my village, I hear words which were used in my childhood and I get thrilled. The words are sweet to hear and great emotion hides in it. Learning English language is not a bad thing but at the same time, we must remember our roots and our language. This egged me on to start this group to share words with my friends. Within a week, the group went viral and many joined the group and shared the words they familiar with,‚Äù said Sudheer Kumar Thandra.\nIn Telangana, one can witness that each district has its own words and usage. For example, paddy is called with various names that includes ‚ÄòMallisannalu‚Äô, ‚ÄòDoodibongaralu‚Äô, ‚ÄòBangaru Teegalu‚Äô, ‚ÄòGodavari Isukalu‚Äô, ‚ÄòErramallelu‚Äô, ‚ÄòSurekhalu‚Äô, ‚ÄòHamsalu‚Äô and more. Sudheer said that paddy has 70 different names in Telangana. Sudheer Kumar along with Samala Naveen Reddy, Vijay Kumar, Swarna Kilaru, Naresh, Regonda Rajendra Prasadh are managing the group. \nMany writers and poets too joined and suggested. Eminent people like Nandhini Sidha Reddy and Allam Narayana also share their posts in the group.\nSama Naveen Reddy, one of the group member said, \"Many people think that the Telangana language is only a dialect, but it has unique vocabulary that derived from daily lives of people. A poetic expression lies in it, that gives sweetness to communication. Through the group, we are bringing old words back. Recollecting those old memories is always a refreshing and emotional among our members. Telangana state is discovering its identity in every aspect and we as a Facebook group are adding our bit.\"\nSharing about the functioning of the group, Sudheer said, ‚ÄúAnyone can share any word in the page. If one shares a word, then everyone shares what they call the same in their locality with images and also gives description. Our writers, poets, and historians in the group check the real meaning and shares with everyone. When we read a new word in the group, we recollect the memories we had with the word and feel happy,‚Äù\nSudheer informed that more than 15 words will be shared every day in the group and the count doubles during weekends.\nWhen asked about the first word which shared on the group, Sudheer said,‚ÄúWe posted the word ‚ÄòGadigolu‚Äô on the page and it means ‚Äòrestrict something to enter in a place‚Äô. Until today, more than 8,000 words are shared in the group by more than 6,700 members. We conduct meetings with group members to improve. Recently, we met in the World Telugu Conference held in Hyderabad.‚Äù\nSudheer informed, ‚ÄúWe are planning to launch a website with the same name to reach out to more people. We will also launch an app in near future. Telugu University is compiling a book of 1 lakh Telangana words and they collected 60,000 already. ‚Äù \nBOX\n\nHere is a sample of words and how they changed over time.\n\nThen          Now
